<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp2sec2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>GCD</title>

  <p> </p>

  <definition xml:id="definition-common_divisor">
    <title>Common Divisor</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If  <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> are integers and there is an integer <m> d </m> that divides both of them, then <m> d </m> is a <term>common divisor</term> of <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>



  <definition xml:id="definition-gcd">
    <title>Greatest Common Divisor (GCD)</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If  <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> are integers, if <m> g </m> is a common divisor of <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> such that if <m> d </m> is any other common divisor of <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m>, then <m> g \ge d</m>,  then <m> g </m> is the <term>greatest common divisor (gcd) </term> of <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<p>
  We denote the gcd of integers <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> by <m>\gcd(a,b)</m>.
</p>

<p>
  The following proposition is foundational for the rest of this chapter.  It is a consequence of the division algorithm and the well-ordering principle.
</p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-gcd_and_division_algorithm">
  <title>GCD and the Division Algorithm</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b,q,r\in \Z</m> where <m>b &gt; 0</m> and <m>a = bq+r </m>, then <m>\gcd(a,b) = \gcd(b,r)</m>. 
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  First show that any common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is also a common divisor of <m>b</m> and <m>r</m>.  Then show the converse.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/>, <xref ref="definition-common_divisor"/>, <xref ref="definition-gcd"/>, <xref ref="proposition-divisibility_of_linear_combination"/>  useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<proposition xml:id="proposition-euclidean_algorithm">
  <title>The Euclidean Algorithm</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b\in \Z</m> where <m>b &gt; 0</m>, then using the division algorithm repeatedly:
      <md>
        <mrow>a  \amp= bq_1 + r_1 \amp\amp\text{where } 0 \le r_1 &lt; b,</mrow>
        <mrow>b  \amp= r_1 q_2 + r_2 \amp\amp\text{where }0 \le r_2 &lt; r_1,</mrow>
        <mrow>r_1  \amp= r_2 q_3 + r_3 \amp\amp\text{where }0 \le r_3 &lt; r_2,</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp\vdots \amp\amp</mrow>  
        <mrow>r_{n-2}  \amp= r_{n-1} q_{n-1} + r_n \amp\amp\text{where } 0 \le r_n &lt; r_{n-1},</mrow>
        <mrow>r_{n-1}  \amp= r_n q_n. \amp\amp</mrow>
      </md>
      Let <m>r_{n}</m> be the last positive remainder.  Then <m>\gcd(a,b) = r_n</m>. 
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  How do you know the process terminates?  Can you find a nonempty decreasing sequences of positive integers?  You may find  <xref ref="proposition-division_algorithm"/>, <xref ref="definition-well-ordered"/>, and  <xref ref="proposition-gcd_and_division_algorithm"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


<p>
  The Euclidean Algorithm is truly an amazing algorithm.  If you go and inspect your proof, you will see that you iterate the division algorithm no more than <m>2\log_2(b)+1</m> times!  This is a very efficient algorithm for computing the gcd of two integers.  Even though it is over two thousand years old, it is still state-of-the-art and has profound applications in number theory and beyond.
</p>

